subSection.paragraph:
Mites were collected and mounted in either PVA or Hoyer′s medium ( Walter & Krantz 2009 ) directly from field collected samples, and were examined, measured and illustrated at 1000×, and photographed at 200× and 400×, using a DIC Nikon Eclipse 80 iTM . All measurements are presented in micrometers (μm) and as the range followed by the measurements for the holotype (when examined) in square brackets (n. b.: as the holotype of the
E. quadrisetosus
is a deutonymph, the description of the deutonymph for this species has holotype measurements; in addition, the adult female description of
E. quadrisetosus
also includes measurements of the junior synonym
E. gibbus
holotype ). Both setae in every pair of setae on all specimens were measured for the descriptions. Body size was measured between dorsal setae v2–h1 for length and between sc2–sc2 for width (
Saito et al. 1999
). Setae were measured from the centre of the setal base to the tip of the seta; distances between setae were measured as the distance from the centre of one setal base to the other. Leg setal numbers are written as the total number of phaneres followed by number of solenidia in parentheses. Leg segments are abbreviated as follows: coxa cx, trochanter tr, femur fe, genu ge, tibia ti, tarsus ta. Setal shape terminology follows Beentje (2010) , and cuticle sculpture patterns follow Harris (1979) . Leg and body setation follows Lindquist (1985) (who adapted it from Grandjean (1939)) , as was presented in the theses of both Quiros-Gonzalez (1985) and Kane (2003) , and is increasingly being applied by many subsequent authors (e.g., Zhang & Fan 2004 ; Xu & Fan 2010 ; Seeman & Beard 2011 ;
Xu et al. 2013
;
Beard et al. 2014
, 2016 ;
Castro et al. 2016a
, b, 2017 ;
Welbourn et al. 2017
;
Beard et al. 2018
).

